{{EngvarB|date=April 2017}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}
The '''Gupta era''' is a historical [[calendar era]] that begins from 318–319 CE. It was used by the [[Gupta Empire|Gupta emperors]], as well as their vassals and their successors in present-day northern India and Nepal. It is identical to the '''Vallabhi era''' (or Valabhi era), which was used in the [[Saurashtra (region)|Saurashtra]] region of western India, although regional differences lead to a slightly different calculation for the conversion of Vallabhi era years to [[Common Era]] (CE).

== History ==

The Gupta era is now believed to have been started by the [[Gupta Empire|Gupta kings]], although there have been several debates over its origin in the past. The 11th century Persian writer [[Al-Biruni]], who described the Guptas as "wicked", incorrectly stated that the Gupta era marked the end of the Gupta dynasty. He dated the beginning of the Gupta era to the year 241 of the [[Shaka era]], that is, 318–319 CE. Al-Biruni's claim later led to debates about the era's origin among the 19th century historians.{{sfn|Ashvini Agrawal|1989|pp=99–100}}

[[John Faithfull Fleet]] analysed the Gupta inscriptions, and realised that they were dated to years of a particular calendar era. He believed that the era was founded by king Jayadeva of the [[Licchavi (kingdom)|Lichchhavi]] dynasty (relatives of the Guptas), and was later adopted by the Guptas.{{sfn|Ashvini Agrawal|1989|pp=98–99}}

Later discoveries and analysis indicate that the era was actually founded by the Guptas, and was known after them. For example:{{sfn|Ashvini Agrawal|1989|p=98}}

* The [[Mathura]] stone pillar inscription, issued by [[Chandragupta II]], is dated to the year 61 "following the era of the Guptas" (''Gupta-kālā nuvartamāna'').{{sfn|Ashvini Agrawal|1989|p=98}}
* The [[Sarnath]] inscriptions of [[Kumaragupta]] and [[Budhagupta]] also refer to the Gupta era.{{sfn|Ashvini Agrawal|1989|pp=98–99}}
* The [[Junagadh]] rock inscription of [[Skandagupta]] mentions the phrase ''Gupta-prakāle'' or ''Guptasya-kāle''.{{sfn|Ashvini Agrawal|1989|p=98}}
* The [[Ganjam]] copper-plate inscription from the reign of [[Shashanka]] is dated to year 300 of the Gupta-era (''Gauptabda varsha-shatatraye'').{{sfn|Ashvini Agrawal|1989|p=99}}

[[Georg Bühler]] concluded that the Gupta era was started by [[Chandragupta I]] in 318–319 CE, to mark his coronation. This is the most prevalant theory about the era's origin now.{{sfn|Ashvini Agrawal|1989|pp=100–101}} However, this cannot be said with certainty, and the era may have been started by his predecessors or his son [[Samudragupta]] as well.{{sfn|D. C. Sircar|1965|p=285}} Some other theories trace the origin of the era to 3rd century CE or earlier, but this view is now discredited: the 7th century inscription of Shashanka is dated to the 300th year of the Gupta era, and proves that the Gupta era started in the 4th century.{{sfn|Ashvini Agrawal|1989|p=101}}

== Usage ==

The Gupta era was used in [[North India|northern India]], [[West India|western India]] and parts of [[East India|eastern India]] until the end of the Gupta dynasty in the 6th century CE.{{sfn|Richard Salomon|1998|p=186}}

Apart from the Gupta rulers, the Gupta era was also used by their vassals and successors, such as:

* the [[Maitraka|Maitraka dynasty]] of [[Vallabhi]]: this resulted in the era being called the "Vallabhi" era in the Maitraka-ruled territory.{{sfn|D. C. Sircar|1965|p=285}}{{sfn|Richard Salomon|1998|p=186}}
* [[Shashanka]]{{sfn|Ashvini Agrawal|1989|p=99}}
* [[Parivrajaka dynasty]] of central India{{sfn|Om Prakash Misra|2003|p=8}}
* [[Uchchhakalpa dynasty]] of central India{{sfn|Om Prakash Misra|2003|p=8}}

== Conversion to CE ==

According to the calculations of [[John Faithfull Fleet]], the Gupta era began on the first day of the [[shukla paksha]] (bright fortnight) of the [[Chaitra]] month. Depending on regional conventions, the process of converting the Gupta era years to [[Common Era]] (CE) years is different:{{sfn|Richard Salomon|1998|pp=186–187}}

* The early inscriptions dated in the Gupta era followed the scheme prevalent in northern India: the first month of the year is Chaitra (''[[chaitradi]]''), and the month starts from the [[full moon day]] (''purnimanta'').
** The year mentioned in these inscriptions is generally the current year at the time of issuance. Thus, the date of these inscriptions can be converted to CE by adding 320 or 321.
** If the year mentioned in the date is the expired year (that is the preceding year at the time of issuance), the date can be converted to CE by adding 319 or 320.

* The later inscriptions from the Maitraka territory ("Vallabhi era") follow the scheme prevalent in southern and western India: the first month of the year is [[kartik (month)|kartika]] (''[[karttikadi]]''), and the month starts from the [[amavasya|new moon day]] (''amanta''). Because of this, the dates are set back by 5 months.
** For the inscriptions that mention the current year, the date can be converted to CE by adding 319 or 320.
** For the inscriptions that mention the expired year, the date can be converted to CE by adding 318 or 319.

